                <head>373. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a statement issued in Tehran on August 5, 1954, Dr. Ali Amini, Chairman of the
                    Iranian delegation to the oil talks, and Howard Page, Chairman of the
                    negotiating group representing the oil company consortium, announced an
                    agreement “which will restore the flow of Iranian oil to world markets in
                    substantial quantities.” Under the agreement, two operating companies would be
                    formed to run the oil fields and refinery in Iran on behalf of the <gloss
                        target="#t_NIOC_1">NIOC</gloss> (National Iranian Oil Company). The <gloss
                        target="#t_NIOC_1">NIOC</gloss> would in turn sell crude and refined oil to
                    an international consortium of oil companies. The agreement would remain in
                    force for 25 years, with the possibility of three 5-year extensions thereafter.
                    For the text of the announcement, see Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                        >Bulletin,</hi> August 16, 1954, pages 232–233.</p>
            </div>
